I will sometimes pause to appreciate an especially clever clue or theme, so speed is clearly not my priority.  :)

@Bill in Yokohama 
It would seem as if what you say would be true. However, it is the terminology long used in baseball, referring only to the runners on base, not the batter.
From Sportslingo.com:"To clear the bases in baseball occurs when a batter gets a timely hit with one or more runners on base, and it allows them to all cross home plate safely. This type of hit can anything from a home run to a basic single, as long as it gives the baserunners enough time to reach home. However, this phrase is typically used when there are two or more runners on base, and the batter hits an extra-base hit that clears the bases and sends everyone home. Also, if a one of the runners is thrown out, this term is not typically used."

